<ce:para>When the diligent French Prof. Pierre Jollès edited the 1996 book on "Lysozymes: Model Enzymes in Biochemistry and Biology" he highlighted what the discoverer of lysozyme, Sir Alexander Fleming, previously prophesized: "We shall hear more about the important protein: lysozyme". Our reflection on the potential targets for which lysozyme was evolutionarily and defensively directed, the bacterial peptidoglycan and the fungal chitin, as obligatory and polyvalent predators, was inspiring. Not ignoring the above milestone enzyme specificity question, fast and low cost purification procedures which include an emphasis on foam fractionation were broached in this overview, the later technology also encompassing the detergent-assisted variant and surfactant removal with an artificial chaperone such as β-cyclodextrin. Accordingly, a literature search of the many papers, book chapters, and patent requests has revealed that, even restricting the search to the not-completed 2012 and 2011 years, there were more than 400 references and 50 patent requests from which about 150 were selected for this review with a few further creative additions from previous years. This bibliographic capture, attesting to the scientific importance and impact of lysozyme, was guided just by the key-word lysozyme. Here we have restricted the references to the category of purification, further distributed into eleven subcategories from foam fractionation, passing by chromatography, until combined enrichment or purification procedures. © 2013 by Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.</ce:para>
